      <focus/>
      <content>Define change management, access restrictions, physical/logical access, tampering. Introduce NIST SP 800-53 Rev 5 CM-5: 'Define, document, approve, and enforce physical and logical access restrictions for changes to systems.' Common misconceptions: Logical access = passwords only; physical irrelevant for software changes.</content>
    </layer>
    <layer level="2" name="Layer 2">
      <focus/>
      <content>Break down CM-5 family: CM-5(1) define/document; CM-5(2) automate enforcement; CM-5(3) dual authorization. Relate to PE-3 (physical), AC-3 (logical). Misconception: Physical/logical controls are interchangeable.</content>
    </layer>
    <layer level="3" name="Layer 3">
      <focus/>
      <content>Step-by-step: 1) Document authorized personnel/roles; 2) Implement via RBAC/tools (e.g., signed updates, CCB approval); 3) Audit/review changes. Examples: Firmware updates require physical badge + logical MFA.</content>
    </layer>
    <layer level="4" name="Layer 4">
      <focus/>
      <content>Link to SCRM (prevent vendor tampering), automation (e.g., CI/CD pipelines with signed components), zero-trust. Optimize for DevOps. Case: SolarWindsâ€”lacked CM-5 enforcement. Sources: NIST SP 800-53 Rev 5 (https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/53/r5/upd1/final), CSF.tools (https://csf.tools/reference/nist-sp-800-53/r5/cm/cm-5).</content>
    </layer>
